Jun 8 2009 	This hotel is dirty.	When I approached La Reserve from the street I was very pleased with what I saw, but don't be duped by the plush exterior as this is massively deceiving: When I tried to check in, I was told that the hotel was full and my booking had been cancelled due to an issue with the payment card, but sensing somehow this was unacceptable the manager found me a room which evidently belonged to someone else judging by the &quot;welcome note&quot; and disgusting-looking bowl of fruit.My room was in the basement, and the first thing that hit me when I stepped into the corridor was the smell of thick cigarette smoke, despite the huge &quot;NO SMOKING&quot; sign on the wall. My room was unclean-feeling with strange burns all over the dirty carpet, and all the furniture was battered and falling apart - the glass wardrobe door was cracked and cellotaped together, and I couldn't get a single channel on the old 1980s television. The curtains were dirty, and the duvet in the cupboard looked as though it hadn't been washed for a long time. After finding a brown-stained towel hanging in the bathroom, I asked to be moved rooms as the smell of smoke was making my eyes sting.The following day I was moved to an upstairs room. Again the furniture was very old and worn out, windows dirty, and curtains which didn't meet in the middle. Again the room had a very un-clean feel about it, with a selection of 4 duvets in the cupboard - each badly stained with various body fluid. The television had no remote control, and the hairdryer worked for about 5 seconds before smoking and conking out. I wore shoes throughout my stay as I couldn't face walking bare-foot on the carpet or bathroom floor.Breakfast consisted of yesterday's stale criossants and bowls of tinned fruit (peach slices in syrup, pear halves in syrup). The orange juice had a funny taste and I had no idea how to make a cup of tea so I didn't bother with breakfast for the rest of my 4 day stay. The bar was unwelcoming and always devoid of people, despite the hotel being full.The only good thing going for this hotel is the location - perfectly positioned for Earl's Court via Fulham Broadway tube station, but it really isn't worth staying here. This hotel is dirty, shoddy, generally unclean-feeling wherever you go, and the service is poor. An absolute rip-off!	
Mar 13 2009 	Good Value Budget Hotel	I have just had two nights in this hotel and cannot understand the very derogatory and negative reviews posted quite recently by others. I was one of a party involved in a show at Earls Court and a total of 9 persons occupied 8 different rooms over 3 nights and not a single one had any complaints at all about the standard of the rooms and hotel facilities. My own room was of quite a reasonable size with a double bed (it may have been 2 singles joined together but if so it was not noticeable) with a good sized bathroom. Both were spotlessly clean and the bed linen was crisp and clean. The bedroom furniture was perhaps a little dated but nevertheless perfectly acceptable. The hotel is well situated on the Fulham Broadway road just a short walk from the underground station so quite convenient for travel into central areas for shopping and shows etc. Breakfast included in the price was an acceptable Continental variety with plenty of cereals and fresh fruits plus bread rolls and croisettes etc and a cooked English breakfast was available at a small extra charge. The hotel may not be up to a 4 or 5 star standard like the Ritz or Dorchester but then neither is the cost and it is certainly a good 2 star rating. I can certainly recommend it as a good base for anyone visiting London.	
